name: Bright Double Room with FREE WiFi
host_about:
I'm a gay man who lives with my partner in Wellington - we've been together since 1993. He's a Kiwi and I'm a Pom, so that explains how we met in Newcastle upon Tyne where he was working during an OE.

name: Te Huia - A Private Escape
description:
Private and secluded, the two-bedroom purpose-built Te Huia sits nestled into the hillside and enjoys expansive views over the Pacific Ocean. It is a quiet and peaceful place to relax and unwind. Backing onto a forest reserve you will enjoy a vast variety of native birds around the house. Wander through the bush track and listen to the Kiwi calling at dusk. Amazing white beaches and fantastic hiking trails are close by for the active explorer
Full or semi-catering by private chef available.
neighborhood_overview:
Whangarei Heads is a 6000 ha peninsula and is well known for its outstanding scenic beauty and amazing coastal walks and hikes. The Mt Manaia hike is recognised as one of New Zealand top 14 short walks and Bream Head/Te Whara trail as of of the top 5 day hikes. The views from any of the many trails are simply outstanding.

Bream Head Scenic reserve is a coastal forest reserve. It is a rich archaeological landscape resulting from more than 500 years of Maori occupation.

On the Harbourside there are numerous sheltered beaches and waterways and on the Pacific oCean side you will find the most incredible white sandy beaches. Kilometres of beach!! Ocean Beach is surf-patrolled in summer.

Slightly further you have Tutukaka where boat trips head to the Poor Knights Islands. Most of our visitors do this trip. Highly recommended for a day out.
host_about: After travelling for 12 years working in the super yacht industry we have decided to make beautiful New Zealand home. We live in an amazingly beautiful area and we love sharing it with others. Conservation is a huge part of our work here. Our high end service background reflects in everything we do here and we love sharing our slice of paradise with visitors. Thoroughly enjoy meeting new folks from all over the world.

name: Ann's Cottage - By The Sea!
description:
Cute, self contained cottage just a one minute walk to the beach. Easy to locate with room to park offstreet.
Free wifi.
Less than 10 minutes walk to supermarket, shops and cafes. One hour drive to The Pancake Rocks at Punakaiki and 1.5 hours to Franz Josef Glacier.
neighborhood_overview:
The cottage is situated in a quiet street. Make sure that you take the time to walk out the gate, across the road and along a few houses to gain access to the beach. It's a wild West Coast beach that is great to walk along.
Also take a walk back to the main highway to see the glowworms after dark.

What else can you do while here?

* Take a drive out to Lake Kaniere then on to Hokitika Gorge.
* A walk along the wild beach, check out the amazing driftwood sculptures.
* Fish and chips at Sunset Point and watch the sun go down
* Drive to the pancake rocks at Punakaiki
* At night, visit the glow worm dell 5 mins from the cottage
* Shop at one of the many tourist shops offering every sort of craft. It's a great place to buy gifts to take home.
*Spend time watching jade carving or glassblowing
* Visit the Tree-top Walkway.
* Get some exercise at the Hokitika Town swimming pool. It's heated and covered. Opens at 6am.

neighborhood_overview:
A good website for our area is www.cromwell.org.nz
Cromwell was originally known as "The Junction", being at the confluence of the Clutha and Kawarau Rivers. In 1862, gold was discovered below the Junction by two miners, Hartley and Reilly. Once the word of a gold strike was out, there was an influx of several thousand miners to the area.

As gold ran out, Cromwell became the service centre for an extensive farming and stone fruit growing area. It has a strategic location between the Lindis and the Haast passes, and acts as a hub between the towns of Wanaka, Queenstown and Alexandra. Cromwell is commemorated with the giant sculpture of stone fruit which stands outside the northern end of the town.

neighborhood_overview:
Situated at the top of New Zealand’s South Island and adjacent to the Abel Tasman National Park, Wainui Bay has a slow pace of life with an abundance of natural beauty - perfect for a holiday retreat.
Many elements of New Zealand life the way it used to be, are still remaining in Wainui Bay. There’s a small family run farm, lots of native birds and no shops and people still have time to go to the beach.
When it comes to natural beauty, Wainui Beach is one of Golden Bay's finest examples and is within easy walking distance of Golden Bay Hideaway. It's a great beach for swimming or exploring the rock pools and sandspit. Standup paddleboarding or kayaking are highly recommended!!
If you pick your tides, a rock-hopping trek to Taupo Point is an adventurous highlight with an old Maori pa site, historical links to Abel Tasman and the first landing of Europeans in New Zealand. Taupo Point is a special place and is considered to have sacred value to the local community and iwi.

name: Chalet Celadon
description: Large two story house with kitchen and laundry facilities. Great for families and long stays. There is private parking and great views out over the beautiful bush to the ocean and the setting sun.
neighborhood_overview: Relaxed vibe, access to everything you could need, beaches and forest plus a picturesque little town.
host_about:
5 years ago, my father Ray asked me to come back to Coromandel and take over his business so he could retire.  As he had built the buildings himself and spent so much time breaking in the land which originally was a derelict farm covered in gorse and pine trees, he didn't want to be parted from the property.  Having grown up in Coromandel until I was 11 years old, I was happy to come back to take over the business and support my dad.  

One year into the process (three and a half years ago now) I had my daughter Ophelia who has made my life busier than I could have ever imagined.  I didn't realise too how much work and upkeep goes into maintaining a large property with many buildings on it!  I have worked so hard over the last 5 years with my main focus being on renovating interiors and re-painting window sills e.g  The journey will continue as we start fixing roofs!

My father and I run the property together and we don't use any pesticides or sprays to manage weeds.  I am a bee keeper,so every flower I have a desire to protect even if it is a weed!  All the cleaning products we use are eco-friendly and we try to do a lot of the laundry ourselves which is a big job in itself.  By drying the sheets on the line as much as possible we are doing our bit for the environment.  The hot water for the Studio and the Tree house is heated by the solar panel in the summer and then in the winter by the fire.  

2018 sparks a new year of change for us.  Last year we got the driveway re done and this year we have renovated the Garden Studio and painted it cream and installed a heat pump. Better signage is in the pipeline then once a few other things are complete we will get started with a big project building another 2 bedroom cabin!  

We work as hard as we can to offer our guests the best stay possible and we really value your feedback.  We look forward to hosting you and hope you enjoy your stay!

name: Hereweka garden Retreat- Luxury Eco
neighborhood_overview: We are close to all the wild life attractions on the Otago Peninsula. The Retreat is nestled in a secluded sunny valley away from traffic noise. We have no light pollution so a perfect place to stay if you are a Stargazer
host_about:
Your hosts at Hereweka Garden Retreat are Peter Cooke and Anna Moore. Peter is the local Portobello General Practitioner while Anna works as a psychotherapist in Private Practice in Dunedin. Both now work part-time so they have opportunities to follow their other passions.

Anna and Peter met at University, and right from the start shared a passion for the natural environment, gardening, organics and sustainable practices. In 1983, with two young children, they fell in love with this property and felt that many of their dreams could be realised here. They purchased the property and named it Hereweka Garden.
Building a Luxurious Garden Retreat on the Otago Peninsula
Quite apart from the beauty of the surroundings there were many other aspects to this property which gave it huge potential. It was situated on a sheltered north-facing slope with a unique micro-climate allowing for a huge variety of plants to be grown. A ridge of original native forest had miraculously survived the plunder of clearing, burning and logging. There was abundant wildlife; both on the property and within easy reach of it.

Everything fell into place. The general practitioner for the area had recently left and Peter began practicing medicine as the local doctor. The medical practice had run down, so initially Peter was working part-time and spent his precious free hours developing Hereweka Garden Retreat. Anna stayed at home to look after their growing family - two more children were born here - and helped Peter develop the garden and nursery.
Stunningly Beautiful Ecological Accommodation 
Since then, Peter and Anna have turned their dream into a reality. Today Hereweka Garden Retreat has a three acre garden, including a large organic vegetable garden and orchard. The ridge of native trees is protected by a QE II National Trust open space covenant, with the rest of the property  planted out in several hundred exotic trees, many of which are rare and unusual. The property is managed by organic, sustainable methods. Open by appointment to visitors, it has become well-known and has been featured several times in major New Zealand garden magazines.
